"""
original | Isaiah | 41-43 | python3 scripts/zc-original-isaiah-41-43.py

Key translation decisions:
- Isa 41:4: YHWH 'I was first and I am with the last' -- the I-am formula anticipating Rev 1:17; 22:13
- Isa 41:29: ruach='wind/futility' for the idols' breath -- not the divine Spirit; context determines sense
- Isa 42:1: nefesh='delight' (nefshi 'my soul' as intensive idiom) + ruach='Spirit' on him (Matt 3:16 / 12:18)
- Isa 42:3: emet='faithfully' -- justice brought forth in truth/faithfulness, not harshly
- Isa 42:6: berit='covenant' -- Servant as covenant-for-the-people, not merely 'contract'
- Isa 42:8: kavod='glory' -- the LORD will not give his glory to another; this is a claim about divine uniqueness
- Isa 42:14: me-olam='for a long time' -- olam as duration/age-long rather than absolute eternity here
- Isa 43:10: aman='believe/trust' + yada='know' -- the witness vocabulary of covenantal acknowledgment
- Isa 43:15: melek='your King' -- YHWH as Israel's King, not merely political title
- Isa 43:25: 'I, I am the one who blots out' -- emphatic double first-person pronoun; grace as divine self-motivation
"""
import json, pathlib
ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

ISAIAH = {
"41": {
"1": "<p>The great courtroom scene opens: coastlands summoned to silence, nations called to renew their strength, and then to come near to speak. The silence first -- no speech from the defendant until the court is formally assembled. The forensic framework (lawsuit, case, arguments) will run through ch 43. The MKT's <em>let them come near and then speak</em> captures the procedural sequence: assemble, then present your case. Together (<em>yachdav</em>) they are to draw near for judgment.</p>",
"2": "<p><em>Melek</em> (king, disp 2) is flagged -- <em>he delivers nations before him and treads down kings.</em> The conqueror from the east is Cyrus of Persia, the LORD's anointed instrument (44:28; 45:1), who came from the east and defeated kings with remarkable speed. The MKT renders the kings as the objects of Cyrus's conquest. The key translation question is whether this is primarily historical (Cyrus) or typological (the ultimate Conqueror who defeats death and its principalities) -- the MKT allows both.</p>",
"3": "<p><em>Shalom</em> (peace, disp 2) is flagged -- the MKT renders <em>traveling paths his feet have never trodden before</em>. The Hebrew <em>shalom</em> here means safely/unharmed rather than covenantal peace -- <em>be-shalom</em> means in safety, in wholeness, without being pursued successfully. The conqueror passes through without hindrance, as if the resistance simply melts away. The MKT's <em>safely</em> is the correct sense in this military-transit context.</p>",
"4": "<p>YHWH is flagged -- the self-revelation formula: <em>I, the LORD -- I was first, and I am with the last.</em> The Hebrew <em>ani rishon ve-et-acharonim ani-hu</em> is the foundational divine I-am formula of Second Isaiah, claiming to be first and last simultaneously. Rev 1:17 and 22:13 apply this formula to the risen Christ: <em>I am the first and the last.</em> The MKT's rendering is close to the Hebrew word order, preserving the double <em>I</em> (the subject and the predicate) that creates the formula's weight.</p>",
"5": "<p>The coastlands saw the conqueror's advance and were afraid -- the ends of the earth trembled. The reaction of fear at divine action is the expected theophanic response. But their fear drives them not to YHWH but to their own mutual encouragement (v6) and idol-making (v7) -- the same fear that should produce repentance instead produces religious panic that generates more idolatry.</p>",
"6": "<p>The nations encourage each other -- <em>take courage!</em> The mutual reinforcement of the idol-manufacturing culture: craftsman to goldsmith, craftsman to craftsman. The social dimension of idolatry -- it is communally maintained and mutually reinforced -- is Isaiah's consistent observation. No one idol-maker works alone; the system is collaborative. The encouragement (<em>chazaq</em>: be strong!) is the same word used for YHWH's strengthening of Israel (v10); both the idolater and the LORD use it, to opposite ends.</p>",
"7": "<p>The craftsman encourages the goldsmith; the one who smooths with the hammer encourages the one striking the anvil. The manufacturing process is described step by step: the technological competence is real -- the nails are good, the image will not fall -- but the product is nothing. The competent manufacture of nothing is Isaiah's ironic point. The MKT's <em>joins the soldering</em> captures the final stage of metalwork idol-production.</p>",
"8": "<p><em>But you, Israel, my servant, Jacob, whom I have chosen, offspring of Abraham my friend.</em> The contrast after vv6-7 is deliberate: while the nations encourage each other to make nothing, Israel is addressed in terms of covenantal relationship. Three titles: <em>my servant</em>, <em>my chosen one</em>, <em>offspring of Abraham my friend</em>. The word <em>friend</em> (<em>ohavi</em>: the one I love) for Abraham is unique here in the OT -- 2 Chron 20:7 and James 2:23 use it. The covenant history grounds the present promise.</p>",
"9": "<p>YHWH's election of Israel from the ends of the earth and calling from the farthest regions. The <em>you are my servant; I have chosen you and not rejected you</em> language is the anti-rejection formula: the fear that YHWH has cast off his people is explicitly countered. The MKT preserves the geographic scope of the calling: from the ends of the earth -- not from somewhere nearby but from the farthest possible distance, showing the reach of divine calling.</p>",
"10": "<p><em>Elohim</em> is flagged -- <em>do not be dismayed, for I am your God.</em> The four divine actions: I will strengthen you (<em>amatzekha</em>), I will help you (<em>azartikha</em>), I will uphold you (<em>tamakhti</em>) with my righteous right hand. The pattern is past-guarantee-for-future: the same God who called you from the ends of the earth will continue to strengthen, help, and uphold. The right hand of righteousness is the hand that acts in covenant faithfulness.</p>",
"11": "<p>All who are enraged against Israel will be put to shame and disgraced; those who oppose will come to nothing. The reversal formula: the shaming of the shamers, the nothing-ing of those who tried to destroy. The MKT's <em>will come to nothing</em> renders <em>ke'efes</em> (like nothing/zero): not just defeated but reduced to non-being, using the same word for the nothingness of idols (v24, 29).</p>",
"12": "<p>You will seek your adversaries and not find them -- the enemies will simply be absent, not just defeated. The MKT's <em>will be as nothing at all</em> (<em>ke'ayin</em>) is the nothing-formula: total absence rather than merely military defeat. The enemies who once dominated Israel will not be findable -- not because they fled but because they have ceased to exist as a threat.</p>",
"13": "<p><em>Elohim</em> and YHWH are flagged -- <em>For I, the LORD your God, hold your right hand; I am the one who says to you, Do not fear; I will help you.</em> The divine hand holding the human right hand is an intimate protection-image: the same posture as a parent holding a child's hand across a dangerous road. The MKT's <em>hold your right hand</em> is literal; the personal address (<em>I am the one who says to you</em>) makes the divine help personal and direct.</p>",
"14": "<p>YHWH is flagged -- <em>Do not be afraid, O Jacob, you worm; you few men of Israel!</em> The address <em>you worm</em> (<em>tola'at</em>) is remarkable: Israel is not described as a great nation but as a worm, a creature of weakness and smallness. This is not contemptuous but protective -- the divine help is specifically for the weak. The MKT's <em>you worm</em> preserves the shock of the address. The Redeemer (<em>go'el</em>: kinsman-redeemer) is the LORD -- Ps 22:6 uses the same word for the Messiah's self-description in abandonment.</p>",
"15": "<p>The worm-to-threshing-sledge transformation: I will make you a new, sharp threshing sledge with many cutting edges. The transformation is from weakness to instrument -- but the instrument serves YHWH's purposes, not Israel's self-aggrandizement. The mountains threshed and the hills reduced to chaff: the cosmic scope of the renewed Israel's function as YHWH's instrument in the world. The MKT's <em>new, sharp threshing sledge with many cutting edges</em> is literal and vivid.</p>",
"16": "<p>YHWH is flagged; <em>ruach</em> (spirit, disp 4) is flagged -- <em>the wind will carry them away and the gale will scatter them; you will rejoice in the LORD.</em> The <em>ruach</em> here is the natural wind/gale that disperses the threshed chaff -- not the divine Spirit but atmospheric wind. The MKT's <em>wind</em> and <em>gale</em> are correct for this physical context. Then the promised response: <em>you will rejoice in the LORD, glory in the Holy One of Israel</em> -- the covenant joy that follows the divine act.</p>",
"17": "<p><em>Elohim</em> and YHWH are flagged -- <em>I, the LORD their God, will answer them; I, the God of Israel, will not forsake them.</em> The double divine self-identification (LORD their God / God of Israel) for answering the poor and needy seeking water. The divine answer to thirst is the transformation of the landscape (vv18-19): rivers on bare heights, fountains in valleys, wilderness into pools. The material provision is real, not merely spiritual metaphor.</p>",
"18": "<p>Rivers on bare heights, fountains in the middle of valleys, wilderness into pools, dry land into springs of water -- the comprehensive transformation of the arid landscape into a well-watered land. The MKT preserves the environmental specificity: the heights (normally dry), the valleys (normally prone to flooding but here fountains), the wilderness (arid zone), the dry land. Each inhospitable feature becomes hospitable by divine action.</p>",
"19": "<p>The seven trees planted in the wilderness and desert: cedar, acacia, myrtle, olive, cypress, plane, and pine. The seven-tree list is a kind of paradise-restoration catalogue -- the most valuable timber and shade trees of the ancient Near East, now planted in the places of desolation. The MKT's precision in tree identification follows the Hebrew list; some identification is uncertain but the cumulative point is clear: where nothing grew, everything grows.</p>",
"20": "<p>YHWH is flagged; <em>yada</em> (know, disp 2) is flagged -- <em>so that they may see and know, consider and understand together, that the hand of the LORD has done this.</em> The four verbs of apprehension (see, know, consider, understand) all point toward the same recognition: this transformation is the LORD's doing, not natural or human process. The MKT's <em>together</em> (<em>yachdav</em>) preserves the communal dimension of this recognition -- it is not private but shared.</p>",
"21": "<p>YHWH and <em>melek</em> (king, disp 2) are flagged -- the courtroom resumes: <em>Present your case, says the LORD; bring forward your strongest arguments, says the King of Jacob.</em> The idols are called to give evidence. The divine title <em>King of Jacob</em> applies the royal title to the covenantal relationship: YHWH is not merely a universal sovereign but specifically Israel's King. The MKT's <em>King of Jacob</em> is literal, consistent with the election-language of vv8-9.</p>",
"22": "<p><em>Yada</em> (know, disp 2) is flagged -- the challenge to the idols: tell us what the former things were, what they mean, so that we may <em>know</em> their outcome. The idol is challenged to prove its knowledge of past events and future events -- the two realms where divine foreknowledge would demonstrate genuine divinity. The MKT's <em>so we can consider them</em> renders the reflective purpose: the knowledge is sought for evaluation, not mere curiosity.</p>",
"23": "<p><em>Elohim</em> is flagged; <em>yada</em> is flagged -- <em>Tell us what is to come in the future, so that we may know you are gods.</em> The test of divinity: predictive knowledge of the future. The MKT renders <em>yeda</em> (know) as <em>know you are gods</em> -- the knowing is recognition of divine status. The invitation to <em>do good or do evil -- do something</em> is the desperation of an unjust judge allowing anything: if the idols cannot predict, can they at least act? The answer is no.</p>",
"24": "<p>The verdict: <em>you are nothing and your work amounts to nothing; whoever chooses you is an abomination.</em> The nothing-verdict (<em>efes</em>: zero, nothingness) applied to the idols and their makers' work. Choosing idols is an abomination (<em>to'evah</em>) -- the same word used for the Canaanite practices forbidden in Deuteronomy. The courtroom verdict against idolatry is total: not just ineffective but morally offensive to YHWH.</p>",
"25": "<p>I have stirred up one from the north and one from the east -- Cyrus of Persia (from the east/northeast) who will come calling on YHWH's name. The trampling of rulers as on mortar, like a potter treading clay, is the image of the victorious king reducing his enemies to raw material. The MKT preserves the potter-clay image that will be developed in 45:9 and 64:8 for divine sovereignty over creation.</p>",
"26": "<p><em>Yada</em> (know, disp 2) is flagged -- <em>Who declared this from the beginning, so we could know?</em> The repeated rhetorical question exposes the silence of the idols: no one among them declared it, no one foretold it, no one heard their words. The knowledge-through-prediction test has been failed by all the idols and their advocates. The MKT's <em>so we could know</em> preserves the purpose clause that makes the prediction a knowledge-event.</p>",
"27": "<p>YHWH's self-claim: I was the first to declare to Zion, <em>look -- here they are!</em> The divine announcement-priority -- the LORD was first to announce the good news to Jerusalem. The <em>messenger of good news</em> (<em>mevasser</em>) is the word that becomes <em>euangelion</em> in Greek -- the gospel herald. This verse anticipates the great herald-announcement of 52:7 and the NT's appropriation of Isaianic herald-language for the gospel proclamation.</p>",
"28": "<p>I looked and there was no one -- among all the idols and nations, no counselor, no one who could answer. The silence of the idols in the courtroom is complete: not even a single spokesman. The MKT's <em>when I asked them, not one could answer</em> captures the total absence of divine speech from the idols. The contrast with the LORD who speaks throughout this courtroom scene is the structural argument.</p>",
"29": "<p><em>Ruach</em> (spirit/wind, disp 4) is flagged -- <em>their cast images are just wind and futility.</em> Here <em>ruach</em> means wind/emptiness -- not the divine Spirit but the hollow breath of nothing. The MKT's <em>wind</em> is correct for this pejorative use: the images have no more substance than wind. The three parallel nothings (emptiness, comes to nothing, wind/futility) create a total verdict of non-existence for the idol system.</p>",
},
"42": {
"1": "<p><em>Nefesh</em> (soul, disp 3) and <em>ruach</em> (Spirit, disp 4) are flagged -- <em>Here is my servant...my chosen one, in whom I delight; I have placed my Spirit on him.</em> The MKT renders <em>ratseta nafshi</em> as <em>in whom I delight</em> -- using soul as the idiom for the deepest personal pleasure (my soul delights = I fully delight). This is the idiom of deep personal satisfaction, not a clinical description. Matt 3:16-17 and 12:18 quote this verse for Jesus' baptism and healing ministry -- the Spirit descending and the divine voice saying <em>this is my Son in whom I am well pleased</em> draws directly on this verse.</p>",
"2": "<p>He will not shout or raise his voice, or make himself heard in the streets. The quietness of the Servant's ministry is the anti-triumphalist claim: the one on whom the Spirit rests does not announce himself through the normal channels of power and publicity. The MKT's <em>make himself heard in the streets</em> captures the Hebrew <em>velo-yashmi in-hachutz qolo</em>: will not cause his voice to be heard outside/in the street. The Servant's work is done without imperial self-promotion.</p>",
"3": "<p><em>Emet</em> (truth/faithfulness, disp 2) is flagged -- <em>he will bring forth justice faithfully.</em> The MKT renders <em>emet</em> as <em>faithfully</em> rather than <em>truly</em> -- capturing the reliability/steadiness dimension of <em>emet</em> rather than the propositional-truth dimension. The bruised reed not broken and the smoldering wick not snuffed: the Servant's tenderness toward the weak and nearly-extinguished. Matt 12:20 quotes this verse for Jesus' non-coercive healing ministry.</p>",
"4": "<p>He will not grow faint or be discouraged until he has established justice in the earth. The perseverance of the Servant mirrors the gentleness of v3: the same one who will not break a bruised reed will not quit until the whole earth has been reached with justice. The coastlands will wait for his instruction -- the global scope of the Servant's mission (all the way to the coastlands) is established before the specific commissioning of vv5-7.</p>",
"5": "<p>YHWH and <em>ruach</em> (spirit, disp 4) are flagged -- God the LORD (<em>ha-El YHWH</em>) who created the heavens, stretched them out, spread out the earth, who gives <em>neshamah</em> (breath) to the people on it and <em>ruach</em> (spirit) to those who walk on it. The MKT distinguishes <em>neshamah</em> (breath, the animating breath of life, Gen 2:7) from <em>ruach</em> (the vitalizing spirit that animates walking creatures). Both together describe the comprehensive life-giving of the Creator God who is speaking to the Servant.</p>",
"6": "<p>YHWH and <em>berit</em> (covenant, disp 3) are flagged -- <em>I, the LORD, have called you in righteousness...I will make you a covenant for the people.</em> The Servant as <em>berit-am</em> (covenant of/for the people) -- the Servant embodies the covenant rather than merely receiving it. The MKT's <em>a covenant for the people</em> is the correct translation: the Servant is the instrument through which the covenant relationship is established with the people. The pairing with <em>a light for the nations</em> expands the scope to universal. Heb 8:6-13 develops the new covenant the Servant mediates.</p>",
"7": "<p>The Servant's mission: open blind eyes, bring prisoners from the dungeon, release those in darkness. The three acts of liberation -- sight, freedom, and light -- become the vocabulary of Jesus' mission statement (Luke 4:18-19 citing Isa 61:1-2, but the same liberatory cluster). The MKT's <em>dungeon</em> and <em>prison</em> are parallel -- different words for the same confinement. The Servant's mission is physical and spiritual liberation.</p>",
"8": "<p>YHWH and <em>kavod</em> (glory, disp 2) are flagged -- <em>I am the LORD; that is my name; I will not give my glory to another nor my praise to carved idols.</em> The divine-name assertion and the refusal to share glory is one of the most theologically dense statements in Isaiah. The divine name YHWH is what makes this refusal of shared glory non-arbitrary: the covenant name defines a unique divine identity that cannot be distributed to other claimants. The glory (<em>kavod</em>) is the weight/honor that belongs to the one true God. The NT applies divine glory to Christ (John 17:5) without contradiction, since Christ shares the divine name.</p>",
"9": "<p>The former things have come to pass -- YHWH's track record of fulfilled prediction. New things are now declared, announced before they spring up. The pattern of prediction-then-fulfillment is YHWH's way of demonstrating divine reliability and distinction from idols (who could predict nothing, ch 41). The MKT's <em>before they spring up I announce them</em> captures the temporal precedence of divine announcement over historical event.</p>",
"10": "<p>YHWH is flagged -- <em>Sing to the LORD a new song.</em> The new song (<em>shir chadash</em>) called for by the new things: as YHWH does a new thing, the appropriate response is a new song, not the recycling of old thanksgiving forms. The scope of the singing -- from sea-travelers to desert-towns (Kedar) to mountain-tops (Sela) -- is universal. The MKT's <em>ends of the earth</em> matches the scope of the Servant's mission (v4: the coastlands).</p>",
"11": "<p>Kedar (Arabian) and Sela (Edomite) raise their voices -- the non-Israelite peoples of the region joining the new song. The geographical specificity is important: these are not abstractions but named peoples with their own histories and territories, invited into the universal praise. The MKT's <em>villages where Kedar dwells</em> and <em>inhabitants of Sela</em> preserve the historical particularity.</p>",
"12": "<p>YHWH and <em>kavod</em> (glory, disp 2) are flagged -- <em>let them ascribe glory to the LORD and proclaim his praise in the coastlands.</em> The ascription of glory to the LORD rather than to Cyrus (the human instrument) or to the nations themselves is the corrective to the imperial tendency to self-glorify. The coastlands who were terrified (41:5) are now called to praise -- fear transformed into worship.</p>",
"13": "<p>YHWH is flagged -- <em>The LORD marches out like a warrior, like a man of war he arouses his zeal.</em> The divine warrior image: YHWH as a warrior who cries out, shouts, and triumphs over his enemies. This is the same image as Exod 15:3 (the LORD is a warrior) developed in a new context. The zeal (<em>qinah</em>: jealous burning passion) aroused in YHWH is the covenantal-love dimension of divine warfare: he fights for his people because he loves them jealously.</p>",
"14": "<p><em>Olam</em> (ancient time, disp 3) is flagged -- <em>for a long time I have kept silent; I have been still and held myself back.</em> The MKT renders <em>me-olam</em> as <em>for a long time</em> -- the age-long duration rather than absolute eternity. The period of divine silence during exile (<em>olam</em>) is the duration of the people's suffering. Now I will cry out like a woman in labor -- the breaking of divine silence with the urgency and pain of childbirth. The woman-in-labor image for YHWH's speaking is remarkable and maternal.</p>",
"15": "<p>I will lay waste mountains and hills, dry up vegetation, turn rivers to dry land -- the scale of divine action is creation-wide. But this destructive action is in service of the restoration of vv16-17: the clearing away of obstacles to enable the blind to be led. The environmental disruption of v15 creates the leveled path of v16. The MKT preserves the active divine verbs (I will lay waste, I will dry up, I will turn) throughout.</p>",
"16": "<p><em>Yada</em> (know, disp 2) is flagged twice -- <em>I will lead the blind along a road they have not known; I will guide them on paths they have never walked. I will turn the darkness into light before them and the rough ground into a smooth place.</em> The double <em>yada</em> (never known / never walked) emphasizes total unfamiliarity -- the road is completely new, not a familiar path with better lighting. The MKT's <em>never known</em> and <em>never walked</em> are both from the same root, showing the consistency of the Hebrew's emphasis on newness.</p>",
"17": "<p><em>Elohim</em> is flagged -- <em>those who trust in carved idols and say to cast images, You are our gods.</em> The word <em>Elohim</em> in the mouths of the idol-worshippers: they call their images <em>elohim</em>, the plural word for God. The divine name itself is transferred to false objects. Those who do this will be turned back and completely put to shame (<em>bosh yevoshu</em>: double shame-verb) -- the intensity of the shame matches the intensity of the misidentification.</p>",
"18": "<p>The summons to the deaf and blind to hear and see. The deaf and blind of v18 are specifically Israel (as v19 clarifies) -- not the nations' idolaters but the covenant people who have eyes but don't see, ears but don't hear. The command to the blind to look and see is the same paradox as Ezek 12:2: a people who have the capacity for perception but have not used it. The MKT's imperative forms (<em>Hear! Look! See!</em>) match the Hebrew's urgency.</p>",
"19": "<p>YHWH is flagged -- the paradox: <em>Who is blind but my servant, or deaf like my messenger whom I send?</em> Israel is YHWH's servant and messenger -- but the servant is blind, the messenger is deaf. This is the sharpest critique in the chapter: the one commissioned to carry divine sight and hearing to others cannot see or hear. The MKT's <em>my dedicated one</em> (<em>meshullam</em>: the one at peace, completed) maintains the irony of the sealed/complete one being blind.</p>",
"20": "<p>He sees many things but does not take them in; his ears are open but he does not hear. The distinction between seeing and perceiving, hearing and registering -- the physical faculties are present but the responsive capacity is closed. This failure of perception is what the Servant of 42:1-9 will cure in others (vv6-7) but which describes the corporate servant Israel's own condition. The MKT's <em>does not take them in</em> is a good rendering of <em>lo yishmor</em>: does not keep/guard what is seen.</p>",
"21": "<p>YHWH is flagged -- <em>it pleased the LORD, for the sake of his righteousness, to make his law great and glorious.</em> The magnification of the Torah is YHWH's own pleasure and his righteous purpose. The glorious (<em>addir</em>: magnificent, majestic) Torah is the object of the LORD's pleasure. This contrasts with the people's failure to hear (v20): the Torah is magnificent, but the servant Israel has not listened to it. The law is not the problem; the hearing is.</p>",
"22": "<p>The consequence of not hearing: Israel robbed and plundered, trapped in holes, hidden in dungeons, taken as prey, with no rescuer. The prison imagery reverses v7 (bringing prisoners out of dungeons) -- Israel is now in the very dungeon the Servant would release them from. The ones who should carry liberation are themselves imprisoned. The MKT's <em>trapped in holes and hidden in dungeons</em> preserves the double imprisonment-imagery.</p>",
"23": "<p>The rhetorical summons to attention: <em>Who among you will pay attention to this? Who will listen and hear for what is to come?</em> The call to hear (v18) now becomes a question about whether anyone will. The hearing for what is to come means hearing with prospective orientation -- not just registering past events but being formed by divine word to face the future. The MKT's <em>pay attention</em> renders <em>yashev</em>: who will sit/give ear to this?</p>",
"24": "<p>YHWH is flagged -- <em>Who handed Jacob over to plunderers...Was it not the LORD, against whom we have sinned?</em> The theodicy question answered: the LORD handed Israel over. But the reason given is not arbitrary -- it was because they sinned, refused to walk in his ways, and did not obey his law. The acknowledgment of divine agency in the exile (<em>the LORD handed over</em>) is paired with the acknowledgment of Israel's responsibility (<em>against whom we have sinned</em>). Both are necessary for the repentance the text calls for.</p>",
"25": "<p><em>Yada</em> (know, disp 2) is flagged -- <em>it set him ablaze all around, but he did not understand; it burned against him, but he did not take it to heart.</em> The <em>yada</em> here is rendered <em>understand</em>: Israel did not know/understand the divine message encoded in the suffering of the burning anger and the battle poured out. The failure to learn from judgment is the same failure as the failure to learn from blessing (vv18-20): both forms of divine communication are unheard.</p>",
},
"43": {
"1": "<p>YHWH is flagged -- <em>But now, this is what the LORD says -- he who created you, Jacob, and formed you, Israel: Do not be afraid, for I have redeemed you; I have called you by name; you are mine.</em> The <em>but now</em> (<em>ve-attah</em>) after the judgment of 42:24-25 is the hinge of grace. Three foundational acts: created, formed, redeemed. The personal claiming -- <em>I have called you by name; you are mine</em> -- is the covenant-ownership declaration. John 10:3 (the shepherd calls his own sheep by name) draws on this ownership-by-naming language.</p>",
"2": "<p>When you pass through the waters, I will be with you -- the promise of divine presence through danger, not the promise of danger-free passage. The waters will not overwhelm, the rivers will not sweep away, the fire will not burn -- but the passing-through is real. The MKT's <em>when</em> (not <em>if</em>) is correct: these are the conditions of life in a fallen world, and the promise is company, not immunity. The water/fire pair creates a merism: through every kind of danger.</p>",
"3": "<p><em>Elohim</em> and YHWH are flagged -- <em>I am the LORD your God, the Holy One of Israel, your Savior. I give Egypt as your ransom, Ethiopia and Seba in your place.</em> The three divine titles (LORD your God, Holy One of Israel, your Savior) cluster around the ransom-declaration. The nations given as ransom for Israel is a stunning claim: the divine economy values Israel above the great nations. The ransom language is picked up by Jesus (Mark 10:45: the Son of Man came to give his life as a ransom for many).</p>",
"4": "<p><em>Nefesh</em> (soul, disp 3) is flagged -- <em>I will give people in exchange for you and nations in exchange for your life (<em>nafshekha</em>).</em> The <em>nefesh</em> here is Israel's life/being -- YHWH gives nations as the equivalent value. The logic: because you are precious and honored in my eyes and because I love you -- the triple ground of divine action is valuation, honor, and love. The MKT renders <em>nafshekha</em> as <em>your life</em>, correctly -- this is the vital-self, not merely the soul as inner spiritual component.</p>",
"5": "<p>Do not be afraid, for I am with you. The same promise as 41:10 now frames the gathering from all four compass directions: east, west, north, south. The geographical comprehensiveness of the gathering mirrors the comprehensiveness of the diaspora -- wherever the exiles were scattered, the LORD will bring them back. The MKT's <em>from the east...from the west</em> and the corresponding north/south commands follow the Hebrew's deliberate exhaustiveness.</p>",
"6": "<p>The command to the four directions to release and return the exiles: <em>Give them back! Do not hold them back.</em> The divine imperative directed at the compass points treats the whole created order as subject to YHWH's commands. My sons from far away, my daughters from the ends of the earth -- the parental address for the returning community. The MKT's <em>from far away</em> and <em>from the ends of the earth</em> create the widest possible scope.</p>",
"7": "<p><em>Kavod</em> (glory, disp 2) is flagged -- <em>everyone who bears my name, whom I created for my glory, whom I formed and made.</em> Three creation-verbs (created, formed, made) building on the foundational claim of v1. The creation for glory (<em>likhvodi</em>) makes human existence teleologically oriented toward divine glory -- as Paul develops in 1 Cor 6:20 (glorify God in your body). The MKT's <em>created for my glory</em> preserves this teleological dimension.</p>",
"8": "<p>The paradoxical command: bring out the people who are blind -- though they have eyes -- and those who are deaf -- though they have ears. The theological blindness and deafness of Israel is the topic of the legal proceeding that follows: Israel is called as witness but is impaired as a witness because of its own spiritual incapacity. The <em>though they have eyes / ears</em> parentheses are the MKT's rendering of the Hebrew's concessive clause structure.</p>",
"9": "<p><em>Emet</em> (truth, disp 2) is flagged -- <em>who among them declared this, or foretold us what is true?</em> The nations are gathered for the lawsuit; they are challenged to produce witnesses who can declare the former things and announce what is true. <em>Emet</em> as the truth of predictive speech: a true prediction is one that comes to pass. The legal-epistemological framework treats truth as verifiable by historical fulfillment.</p>",
"10": "<p><em>Aman</em> (believe/trust, disp 2) and <em>yada</em> (know, disp 2) are flagged; YHWH is flagged -- <em>You are my witnesses, declares the LORD, along with my servant whom I have chosen -- so that you may know and believe me and understand that I am he.</em> The triple cognitive-response (know, believe/trust, understand) is the goal of the witness-vocation. <em>Aman</em> here means believe/trust -- the covenantal faith-response that follows knowing. The declaration <em>I am he</em> (<em>ani-hu</em>) is the divine identity formula of Second Isaiah, applied in John 8:24,28,58 to Christ.</p>",
"11": "<p>YHWH is flagged -- <em>I, I am the LORD, and apart from me there is no savior.</em> The emphatic double first-person (I, I am) intensifies the divine self-identification. The exclusivity claim -- no savior apart from YHWH -- is the theological conclusion of the preceding witness-structure. Peter quotes this exclusivity language for Christ (Acts 4:12: no other name under heaven...by which we must be saved), applying the Isaianic uniqueness-of-YHWH formula to the risen Jesus.</p>",
"12": "<p>YHWH is flagged -- <em>I declared, I saved, and I proclaimed.</em> The three divine past-actions that constitute the evidence for the claim of v11. Then: <em>You are my witnesses, declares the LORD, and I am God.</em> The witness-declaration closes the section: Israel has witnessed the declaring, saving, and proclaiming; therefore Israel is qualified to testify. The MKT's <em>and I am God</em> is a rendering of <em>ve-ani El</em> (and I am God/El) -- the generic term for deity rather than the personal name, emphasizing the theological claim.</p>",
"13": "<p><em>Even from eternity I am he.</em> The <em>mi-yom</em> (from the day / from ever) anticipates the eternal self-identification formula. No one can deliver from my hand. When I act, who can reverse it? The irreversibility of divine action is the guarantor of the salvation promises: what YHWH saves cannot be unsaved by any other power. The MKT's <em>who can reverse it</em> renders <em>yeshivenah</em>: who can turn it back?</p>",
"14": "<p>YHWH is flagged -- <em>your Redeemer, the Holy One of Israel.</em> The go'el (kinsman-redeemer) title applied to YHWH: the one who has the family obligation to redeem is the LORD himself. The redemption is specifically from Babylon -- YHWH sends against Babylon and brings the Chaldeans down as fugitives. The Redeemer-from-Babylon is the new Exodus figure: as YHWH redeemed from Egypt, so from Babylon.</p>",
"15": "<p>YHWH and <em>melek</em> (king, disp 2) are flagged -- <em>I am the LORD, your Holy One, Israel's Creator, your King.</em> The four divine titles in sequence: LORD (covenant name), Holy One (transcendence), Creator (cosmological sovereignty), King (political/covenantal authority). The MKT renders all four, with <em>your King</em> as the closing title -- making YHWH's kingship over Israel personal and direct. This is the answer to the foreign kings of ch 36 who claimed sovereignty.</p>",
"16": "<p>YHWH is flagged -- <em>This is what the LORD says -- he who makes a way through the sea and a path through the mighty waters.</em> The Exodus-defining act (splitting the Red Sea) is cited as the credential for what follows. The divine track record of sea-path making is the guarantee of the new path through the wilderness (v19). The MKT's <em>mighty waters</em> preserves the Hebrew <em>mayim azim</em>: strong/powerful waters.</p>",
"17": "<p>The Exodus reversal: chariot and horse, army and warrior brought out -- then they lay down, never to rise. The Egyptian army's drowning (Exod 14:27-28) is recalled as the paradigm case of YHWH's military action on Israel's behalf. The MKT's <em>lay down and could not rise; they were extinguished, snuffed out like a wick</em> uses the same wick-imagery as 42:3 (the smoldering wick the Servant will not snuff out) -- but reversed for the enemies: they are snuffed out.</p>",
"18": "<p><em>Do not remember the former things, or consider the events of long ago.</em> The command to forget the Exodus is startling -- Isaiah is consistently Exodus-minded. But the point is: the new thing about to be done (v19) will so surpass the Exodus that clinging to the former thing as the supreme category of divine action would prevent recognizing the greater thing. The MKT's <em>events of long ago</em> renders <em>qadmoniot</em>: ancient/former things.</p>",
"19": "<p><em>Yada</em> (know, disp 2) is flagged -- <em>Do you not see it?</em> The new thing: the LORD is doing a new thing even now, springing up. The way through the wilderness and rivers in the desert are the material shape of the new Exodus. <em>Do you not know/perceive it?</em> -- the <em>yada</em> is the same perception-knowing as throughout the chapter. The new thing is already beginning and the question is whether anyone is perceiving it. The MKT's <em>do you not see it</em> renders the rhetorical invitation to perceive the divine action already in progress.</p>",
"20": "<p>Wild animals will honor YHWH -- jackals and ostriches -- because the LORD provides water in the wilderness and rivers in the desert for the chosen people to drink. The wild animals' response is the creation-praise that C.S. Lewis develops in <em>The Lion, the Witch and the Wardrobe</em> as Narnia responding to Aslan. Even the inhospitable creatures of desolation acknowledge the water-giving LORD. The MKT preserves the specificity: jackals and ostriches, both desert-haunt animals (cf. 34:13-15).</p>",
"21": "<p>The people I formed for myself, that they might declare my praise. The teleological statement: Israel was formed for the purpose of divine praise-declaration. This is the positive counterpart to the failure of vv22-24: the purpose is praise, the reality is silence and unfaithfulness. The MKT's <em>formed for myself</em> renders <em>yatzarti-li</em>: formed for my own sake -- the creation is purposive, not incidental.</p>",
"22": "<p>Yet, Jacob, you have not called on me; you have grown weary of me, O Israel. The contrast with v21 is sharp: formed to declare praise but not calling on the LORD. The weariness (<em>yagata</em>) is the opposite of the renewal-of-strength promised for those who wait on the LORD (40:31 uses the same root). The covenant people are weary of the covenant God -- the deep failure of the relationship.</p>",
"23": "<p>You have not brought sheep for burnt offerings -- the ritual accusations: the sacrificial system has been neglected, but not because YHWH was demanding too much (v23b: I have not burdened you with grain offerings or wearied you with frankincense). The problem is not the burden of the requirements but the people's failure to fulfill them. The MKT's <em>not honored me</em> renders <em>lo kabadtani</em>: not glorified/honored me -- the kavod that belongs to the LORD has not been given.</p>",
"24": "<p>You have not bought me fragrant calamus with money, nor satisfied me with the fat of your sacrifices. Instead you have burdened me with your sins and wearied me with your iniquities. The reversal: the people have not offered their required gifts, but they have given YHWH their sins as an unwanted gift. The MKT's <em>burdened me</em> and <em>wearied me</em> (<em>heevadtani...helo'tani</em>) use the same language as the acceptable worship vocabulary -- inverted. The worship-absence has been filled with sin-presence.</p>",
"25": "<p>YHWH is flagged -- <em>I, I am the one who blots out your transgressions for my own sake, and I will not remember your sins.</em> The emphatic double first-person (<em>anoki anoki hu</em>) makes the forgiveness an act of divine self-motivation: the LORD blots out sins <em>for my own sake</em> (<em>lema'ani</em>), not because Israel deserves it or has offered adequate atonement. The formula <em>I will not remember your sins</em> is the basis of the new covenant in Jer 31:34 and Heb 10:17. The MKT's rendering preserves the emphatic self-referentiality of the forgiveness.</p>",
"26": "<p><em>Shaphat</em> (contend, disp 2) is flagged -- <em>Let us argue the matter together. Present your case, that you may be proved innocent.</em> The courtroom resumes after the accusation of vv22-24 and the forgiveness of v25: can you prove your innocence? The MKT's <em>argue the matter together</em> renders <em>nishpatah yachdav</em>: let us contend/judge together. The invitation to argue your case is a form of grace -- the accused is given the opportunity to speak.</p>",
"27": "<p>Your first ancestor sinned -- either Adam (the universal ancestor) or Abraham/Jacob (the specific covenant ancestor). The intermediaries (<em>melakim</em>: interpreters or go-betweens, possibly the prophets or priests who should have mediated covenant faithfulness) have rebelled. The long history of covenant failure extends from the first ancestor to every intermediary -- the people cannot claim their case has been defended.</p>",
"28": "<p><em>Qodesh</em> (holiness, disp 2) is flagged -- <em>I allowed the sanctuary's leaders to be defiled, and I gave Jacob over to destruction and Israel to scorn.</em> The holy princes (<em>sarei qodesh</em>) -- the priestly/levitical leaders -- defiled and the people given over to destruction. The <em>qodesh</em> applied to the leaders who were supposed to embody holiness but instead led to defilement. The MKT's <em>sanctuary's leaders</em> renders <em>sarei qodesh</em>: the holy/set-apart ones who lead. The chapter ends at the point of judgment -- the restoration promise of 44:1ff will reverse it.</p>",
},
}

def main():
    data = load_comm('mkt-original', 'isaiah')
    merge_comm(data, ISAIAH)
    chs = sorted(data.keys(), key=lambda x: int(x))
    total_v = sum(len(data[c]) for c in chs)
    print(f'Isaiah original: {len(chs)} chapters, {total_v} verses')
    save_comm('mkt-original', 'isaiah', data)

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
